abstract = {Installation of refueling facilities for electric vehicles (EVs) in the range of conventional fuel filling stations demands huge initial investments. It also necessitates the expansion of power grid infrastructure. Furthermore, the problem is critical in remote places and resource-limited environments. One alternative solution for this evaluative problem is to incorporate EV smart charging. Smart charging circumscribes load fluctuations on the grid while charging EVs and paves the way for renewable energy use in recharging EVs. The current study presents a systematic approach to identify and suggest the most effective charging policies for building a smart EV charging station. The study employed a three-step process. First, a critical analysis of smart charging policies from the literature is performed and corresponding control parameters are identified. Secondly, the identified parameters are classified into categories of direct influence, indirect influence, and enhancement parameters. The final step recommends a set of parameters for a smart EV charging station controller, covering the basic design level, real-time operational level, and enhancement level. While numerous studies have explored various EV charging policies, control parameters, and optimization techniques, there is still a lack of procedural approaches for identifying the optimal control parameters specific to a given charging policy. This study aims to address this gap by taking a focused approach that centers on the adoption of a particular charging policy for the development of a smart charging station.}
